
[1]maim

   MAIM, v.t.

   1. To deprive of the use of a limb, so as to render a person less able
   to defend himself in fighting, or to annoy his adversary.

   2. To deprive of a necessary part; to cripple; to disable.

   You maim'd the jurisdiction of all bishops.

                 MAIM, n. [written in law-language, mayhem.]

   1. The privation of the use of a limb or member of the body, so as to
   render the sufferer less able to defend himself or to annoy his
   adversary.

   2. The privation of any necessary part; a crippling.

   Surely there is more cause to fear lest the want thereof be a maim,
   than the use of it a blemish.

   3. Injury; mischief.

   4. Essential defect.

   A noble author esteems it to be a maim in history. [Not used.]
